<div class="hero"><div class="container">
<h1>Tennessee Bankruptcy Exemptions</h1>
<p class="subtitle"><a href="https://bankruptcyexemptionsbystate.com/" title="exemptions">Exemptions</a> determine what property you get to keep when you file bankruptcy. Understanding Tennessee's <a href="https://bankruptcyexemptionsbystate.com/" title="exemptions">exemptions</a> is critical - they can mean the difference between keeping and losing your home, car, and savings.</p>
</div></div>
<section><div class="container">
<h2>What Are Exemptions?</h2>
<div class="card">
<p><a href="https://bankruptcyexemptions.com" title="Bankruptcy Exemptions">Bankruptcy exemptions</a> are laws that protect certain property from being taken to pay your creditors. In <a href="chapter-7.html">Chapter 7</a>, non-exempt property can be sold by the trustee. In <a href="chapter-13.html">Chapter 13</a>, the value of non-exempt property affects how much you must pay through your plan.</p>
<p>Tennessee allows filers to choose between state and federal exemptions. Many filers compare both to determine which provides better protection for their specific assets.</p>
</div>
</div></section>
<section><div class="container">
<h2>Tennessee State Exemptions - Full List</h2>
<div class="card">
<h3>Homestead - $5,000 / $7,500</h3>
<p>Tennessee's homestead exemption protects up to $5,000 of equity in your primary residence for an individual, or $7,500 for a married couple or if you are 62 or older. Tennessee also allows filers to choose federal exemptions instead.</p>
<p style="color:#8b949e;font-size:0.9rem">Tenn. Code Ann. 26-2-301</p>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Motor Vehicle - No specific vehicle exemption under state law (federal: $4,450)</h3>
<p>Protects equity in one motor vehicle up to the exemption limit. If you owe more than the car is worth (you are "underwater"), there is no equity to protect and the exemption is not needed.</p>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h3>Other Tennessee Exemptions</h3>
<table>
<tr><th>Property</th><th>Amount</th></tr>
<tr><td>Household goods, furnishings</td><td>$4,000 total (state)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Clothing</td><td>Included in household goods</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tools of trade</td><td>$1,900</td></tr>
<tr><td>Jewelry</td><td>$1,500</td></tr>
<tr><td>Wildcard</td><td>$10,000 (state wildcard); federal: $1,475 + up to $13,950 unused homestead</td></tr>
<tr><td>Retirement accounts (IRA, 401k, pension)</td><td>Fully exempt</td></tr>
<tr><td>Social Security benefits</td><td>Fully exempt</td></tr>
<tr><td>Workers' compensation</td><td>Fully exempt</td></tr>
<tr><td>Public assistance benefits</td><td>Fully exempt</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
<div class="card" style="margin-top:20px">
<h3>Federal Exemption Alternative</h3>
<table>
<tr><th>Property</th><th>Federal Exemption</th></tr>
<tr><td>Homestead</td><td>$27,900</td></tr>
<tr><td>Vehicle</td><td>$4,450</td></tr>
<tr><td>Household goods</td><td>$700 per item / $14,875 total</td></tr>
<tr><td>Wildcard</td><td>$1,475 + up to $13,950 unused homestead</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tools of trade</td><td>$2,800</td></tr>
<tr><td>Retirement accounts</td><td>Fully exempt</td></tr>
</table>
</div>
</div></section>
<section><div class="container">
<h2>Special Notes</h2>
<div class="card">
<p>Tennessee allows filers to choose between state and federal exemptions. Most Tennessee filers choose federal exemptions because the state homestead exemption is very low, and the federal wildcard provides more flexibility.</p>
</div>
</div></section>
<section><div class="container">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>What is the Tennessee homestead exemption?</summary><div class="answer"><p>Tennessee's homestead exemption protects up to $5,000 of equity in your primary residence for an individual, or $7,500 for a married couple or if you are 62 or older. Tennessee also allows filers to choose federal exemptions instead.</p></div></details>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>How much vehicle equity can I protect in Tennessee?</summary><div class="answer"><p>Tennessee's motor vehicle exemption is No specific vehicle exemption under state law (federal: $4,450). If your car equity is within that limit, you keep it in <a href="https://whatischapter7.com/" title="Chapter 7">Chapter 7</a>.</p></div></details>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>Does Tennessee allow federal exemptions?</summary><div class="answer"><p>Yes. Tennessee allows filers to choose between state and federal exemptions.</p></div></details>
</div></section>
